"Sanhueza E.","Potential emissions of Kyoto and non-kyoto climate active compounds in the production of sugarcane ethanol",2009,"Interciencia","34","1",,"8","16",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-67650096119&partnerID=40&md5=641825384e4f41b1a15fc184ed7f4950","Instituto Venezolano, Venezuela; Laboratorio de Química Atmosférica, IVIC, Apdo. 22117, Caracas 1020A, Venezuela","Sanhueza, E., Instituto Venezolano, Venezuela, Laboratorio de Química Atmosférica, IVIC, Apdo. 22117, Caracas 1020A, Venezuela","Sugarcane ethanol is the most commercially developed liquid biofuel The potential emissions of Kyoto and non-Kyoto Protocol climate active compounds in the production of sugarcane ethanol in agricultural lands are evaluated herein. Various scenarios are considered, such as low or high N 2O emission from Nfertilizers, inclusion or not of pre-harvest burning, uncontrolled or controlled emissions in bagasse based boilers, and 20 or 100 years time horizons in GWPs. The CO 2 emitted in ethanol fuel combustion is recycled during sugarcane ""re-growing"" and does not count as greenhouse gas. However, even though many uncertainties remain, the available information allows estimating that CO 2-eq emissions are very large when ethanol production is based on pre-harvest burning and there is non-controlled particle emission in boilers. In these scenarios, compared with the combustion of equivalent amounts of gasoline, higher CO 2-eq emission would take place. Halting sugarcane field burning would not be sufficient to revert the situation, especially in a 20-years time horizon. Only when more environmental friendly procedures are applied, a significant saving of CO 2-eq emissions occurs at 20 and 100-years horizon scenarios. In all scenarios, non-Kyoto Protocol compounds make an important net contribution. Therefore, if a real evaluation of climate active compounds emissions is to be reached, it would be crucial to include these compounds in life cycles studies. To reduce uncertainties, especially of nonKyoto compounds, additional research is needed.","Bagasse combustion; Black carbon; Global warming; GWPs; Non-kyoto compounds; Sugarcane ethanol",,,,,,,"Amre, D.K., Infante-Rivard, C., Dufresne, A., Durgawale, P.M., Ernst, P., Case-control study of lung cancer among sugar cane farmers in India (1999) Occup. Env. Med, 56, pp. 548-552; Andreae, M.O., The dark side of aerosols (2001) Nature, 409, pp. 671-672; Andreae, M.O., Atlas, E., Cachier, H., Cofer III, W.L., Harris, G.W., Helas, G., Koppmann, R., Ward, D.E., Trace gas and aerosol emissions from savanna fires (1996) Biomass Burning and Global Change, 1, pp. 278-295. , Levine JS Ed, MIT Press. Cambridge, MA, USA. pp; Autrey, L.J.C., Chang, K., Renewable energy from sugar cane biomass in Mauritius: Progress & Prospects (2006) ISSCTProducts Workshop, , http://issct.intnet.mu/cpabst06.htm, Maceio, Brazil 12-16 Nov; Baldani, J.I., Reis, V.M., Baldani, V.L.D., Döbereiner, J., A brief story of nitrogen fixation in sugarcane: Reasons for success in Brazil (2002) Fund. Plant Biol, 29, pp. 417-423; Battye W, Boyer K (2002) Catalog of Global Emissions Inventories and Emission Inventory Tools for Black Carbon. Contract 68. D-98-046. USEPA. Washington, DC, USA. 54 ppBerntsen, T.K., Fuglestvedt, J.S., Joshi, M.M., Shine, K.P., Stuber, N., Ponater, M., Sausen, R., Li, L., Response of climate to regional emissions of ozone precursors: Sensitivities and warming potentials (2005) Tellus, 57 B, pp. 283-304; Berntsen, T., Fuglestvedt, J.F., Myhre, G., Stordal, F., Berglen, T.F., Abatement of greenhouse gases: Does location matter? (2006) Clin. Change, 74, pp. 377-411; Boddey, R.M., Biological nitrogen fixation in sugar cane: A key to energetically viable biofuel production (1995) Crit. Rev Plant Sci, 14, pp. 263-279; Bond, T.C., Sun, H., Can reducing black carbon emissions counteract global warming? (2005) Env. Sci. Technol, 39, pp. 5921-5926; Bond, T.C., Streets, D.G., Yarber, K.F., Nelson, S